<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		If spiritual technology has become currency in digital culture, Edgar Fabián Frías and Nora Berman expose the cost of its exchange. Frías creates portals that refuse Western frameworks of categorization and control, insisting instead on an animist relationality where consciousness extends beyond the human. His work positions queerness and Indigenous futurism as sacred technologies that resist systems designed to divide and displace.
	</p>
	<p>
		Berman, by contrast, reveals how livestreaming stages intimacy as a form of universal engagement—presence without verification, communion with unknowable others. Her durational streams transform Twitch into ritual space while resisting the platform’s extractive demands for consistent content and algorithmic compliance.
	</p>
	<p>
		Read together, Frías and Berman complicate the promise of digital oracles. One opens portals, the other dissolves boundaries. Both unsettle the idea that technological spirituality is neutral or accessible. Their practices suggest that to imagine authentic forms of digital ritual, we must look beyond responsiveness and institutional legibility—toward practices that resist capture altogether.
	</p>
</div>
